The first virtual provider is coming to Czech Republic this year.
Or maybe
The mobile channel market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, which Czech providers offer almost all services as well as those offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider who forces the classic at lower prices.
Maybe he won't wait for a long time.
The fact that the Czech mobile providers are working on the most expensive in Europe at all, we have often reported it at Mobil.cz.
This also confirmed by the telecommunications agency ČTÚ, which noted that the price of a SMS here is higher than the rest of the European Union.
According to the last steps of the European Commission in the area of regulation of roaming fees, it is so likely to be a paradoxal situation - for some of the Czech mobile providers, SMS will be cheaper from abroad than at home.
Why are the prices in Czech Republic so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, it is lacking the competition that really makes a fighting announcement.
It may sound paradox, but in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of much more than 100%.
On the other hand, mobile providers are pleased to shine on the fact that there is extremely much competition in the Czech market.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák, who in the past often expressed that there is no room for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a classic provider with its own network no longer has a lot of chances (although he would probably not even find any frequencies).
However, there is another possibility - a virtual provider.
Just the entry of virtual providers to the mobile phone market led to a significant price drop, to which the classic mobile phone providers also had to respond.
There were still similar voices in the UK before companies such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the UK market.
However, it has been proven that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
You don’t need to look for examples for a long time.
In February, we reported this about the launch of the virtual provider mobilking in Poland.
In just one year and a half, this provider managed to win more than 100 thousand customers and thus rise to the country’s fifth largest provider.
Behind mobilking is the Penta financial group owned in Czech Republic, among other things U:fon.
The advantage of virtual provider is that you can focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to work effectively, virtual providers need much less customers than a classic provider.
They do not need relatively high costs for the construction, operation and entertainment of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually profile themselves as low-cost companies – they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less extensive service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers SMS in the UK at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a fairly good shake to put on a non-climbing target group.
This provider is specifically addressed to men.
“Real guys choose Mobilking – the provider they like and can trust,” said David Seibert, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator company of this virtual provider.
It is hard to say if a similar concept could be seen in Poland as well as in the Czech Republic.
Vodafone Miroslav Čepický’s press speaker also doubts: “The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, he is relatively saturated from the point of view of the service offer.”
In the Czech Republic without chances, the mobile phone providers
However, it is almost certain that when a virtual mobile service provider conquers the Czech Republic, this will not be mobileking.
“We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look very hopeful.
It is more likely to enter the market by mobilking in other countries of our region,” said Janna Studničková, the press spokesman of the Penta Financial Group in a telephone conversation.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile providers in the Czech Republic are not unauthorized in this regard.
On the contrary, they try to do everything to ensure that there is no potential competitor.
Your interest in starting a virtual mobile service provider has long been showing the GTS Novera group who wants to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of company customers.
“We are very interested in providing our customers not only with fixed networks but also with mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this option with all Czech mobile providers.
With some of them, we have already been able to achieve negotiations,” said Pavel Kaidl, the press spokesman of the Group.
Maybe there are better times now.
Non-official information shows that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
But so far, it is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
“Now we do not expect that there is room for a fully virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market has large specifications compared to other markets.
So far, no subject has discussed us with a complex and confident project in this area,” says Vlastimil Sršeň from Telefónica O2.
Other suppliers also indicate the specifics of the Czech market.
T-Mobile's press spokesperson Martina Kemrová, in rare consonance with the O2 statement, added: "In the meantime, we have not yet found a viable and both-sided project on which we could continue to build."
And she adds, "In the network of T-Mobile will hardly appear by the end of the year a virtual provider.
At this moment, we should already have a concrete offer to be able to think so short-term.”
Vodafone focuses its attention rather on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says: “For negotiations with potential virtual providers, we are open, especially in the area of cost and infrastructure sharing.
That’s what we consider from the customer’s perspective as the best.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is looking for a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile internet.”
The responsible authorities - with the suppliers hand in hand
The action of mobile providers is easy to understand, another provider calls more competition, which would lead to lower prices and thus to a decline in profits.
So why should such a competitor make it easier to enter the market?
The fact that the providers can draw on a strang, when it comes to something, also the long hin and her point to the emergence of U:fon.
Probably the strongest pressure towards ČTÚ came at the time when U:fon came into the market, out of the company T-Mobile.
This also shows publicly accessible information from the ČTÚ websites.
But now U:fon is right as an argument why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová noted: “The competitive environment of the mobile phone market has also recently been strengthened by the market entry of a fourth mobile phone provider.
Given the nature of the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new actor would put high demands on the market itself and, in particular, its services."
However, in view of this approach of the mobile providers, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is surprised.
It is not only the attitude of the ČTÚ, which, unfortunately, in the Czech Republic - unlike the UK and other highly developed countries - does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition.
It owns exclusively the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, refers to all of this problem, to its very typical attitude.
The entry into the market would then be possible after a contract between a mobile service provider and a virtual service provider has been concluded on the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded as the offer of potential stakeholders was probably not interesting enough for the classical providers,” said Kristián Chalupa from the UOHS Department of Foreign Relations.
Of representatives of the providers, such a formulation would not be surprised.
This is more than suspicious from an authority that represents consumer interests and, among other things, ensures that no one abuses his position on the market.
In particular, when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In the country where virtual providers work quite normally, it is necessary to observe that their market access has contributed to a price reduction in mobile phone services."
However, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market is likely not one of the interests of ÚOHS.
In this case, it is really shocking that the almost already ongoing conformity of the three mobile providers resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether it really is just an accident is on hand.
As well as the absolute same gasoline price in the gasoline stations is surely only the accident and the consequence of a harsh competition.
"The Authority has not discovered any signs of action against competition in this matter, and therefore it has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the providers has a dominant market position, so he does not have the corresponding increased responsibility for his actions on the market.
The necessary tools for opening the mobile phone market for virtual providers are also likely to lack the telecommunications regulatory authority,” Chalupa said in a statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, developed by ČTÚ, that telecommunications from the perspective of economic competition are a single market.
In such a market, of course, no one of the Czech mobile service providers has a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different perspective - the consent of the network operator is always necessary for a virtual provider to enter the market.
And the mobile service provider has - logically - the monopoly for its network.
This means that in a particular segment he necessarily assumes a dominant position.
Even if you do not agree with this argument, it should be at least a warning for the ÚOHS that three mobile providers will act in a similar manner.
The complaints of a number of stakeholders (including the mentioned company GTS Novera) demonstrate that they face very similar obstacles in negotiations with all providers.
The removal of responsibility for the ČTÚ is then a rather common trick in the telecommunications services, with which the ÚOHS distants itself from the whole issue.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it was not possible to implement the newly adopted Telecommunications Act’s expansion of ČTÚ’s competences in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of professionals had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the UOHS just need to know that too well, but they probably have other interests.
It's going to be when no one looks
Without prejudice, the functioning of any pseudo-virtual providers, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks.
They are companies that spend their own pricing lists for mobile telecommunications services, but are only partly public.
Normally, it is a business that operates in the field of multi-level marketing.
For example, your own mobile phone services offer Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only come from selected ones.
The joke of the matter is that the company appears to the operator as a classic company company that orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile service providers prohibit a similar type of re-sale.
“If there are cases you describe, it can be a violation of the contractual conditions that we will then deal with, which can lead to a cessation of cooperation with the corresponding society,” Martina Kemrová said.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing does not occur with the operators of the mobile service providers.
In particular, in the case of the three mentioned companies, it can be thousands of customers.
However, no operator objects to such action.
Because from the activities of these companies, they do not have negligible profits, at the same time, they are not affected by actual official marketing, unlike the actual virtual providers.
Miroslav Čepický notes possible problems: “The law allows such speculations, despite all, the services of these companies are only used by a very small percentage of customers.
They also have to accept that the SIM card does not run on their phone on their name, so they can’t fully have it like the normal customers of the mobile providers.”
However, at least this would have to happen strangely.
Another question is also open for the UOHS.
The mobile phone providers close their eyes before such a procedure, why do they lock themselves against a virtual provider?
It should be added that ÚOHS has quite strong competences to discover such activities, and if it does not, it does not have to agree with the statement of the providers, they would know nothing about it and their terms and conditions would prohibit this.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has been emphasized several times in the text, the entry into the market of virtual providers led to a significant price drop in the various services.
In practically all countries where virtual providers are created, the classic providers are trying to prevent their emerging virtually more or less.
The arguments used by them were practically identical - a too small or too saturated market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, the regulators intervened right now, which in no way attempted to keep the interests of the mobile providers, but the interests of their customers.
Whether it was through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created, and this followed further.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory organs throw the whole case like a hot potato.
Based on our experiences, we cannot eliminate the impression that unclearness in the competences in these cases is more than affordable.
But we do not throw the flint into the wheat.
