Hepatitis: When to visit the doctor?
About half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected people is estimated to be one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated because patients often do not know they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collection term for infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and yellowing are common, but the stimulants and diseases differ from each other.
Depending on the stimulant, hepatitis viruses spread to two different types: Hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g. through contaminated foods or water), Hepatitis B, C and D viruses can be transmitted through blood and other body fluids (e.g. sperm, separation secret or spice).
Travellers are advised to vaccinate against the viruses A and B, no vaccine against the virus C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear approximately two to three weeks after consuming contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, stomach pain and breakthrough.
Then the yellowness appears on the skin and in the eyes, the chair becomes bright, the urine is dark, and the recovery can take up to two to three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million people die each year from those caused by hepatitis B, much more severe diseases such as liver cancer and liver cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that according to estimates, only every tenth infected is in drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated can lead to liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people don’t even know about their disease, as the stimulant secretly destroys the liver cells - in many cases, the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular inspections, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease occurs more frequently: those who have suffered from blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattoos.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C diseases worldwide is estimated to be 200 million.
Since the disease is already detectable in a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to visit the home doctor with the first signs of unknown origin.
In time, the disease is recoverable, the virus can be eliminated, causing the risk of infection and preventing the formation of cancer.
The 30th of September is the World Hepatitis Day, which is held for the first time in 2004 by patients.
The aim of the action is to strengthen the consciousness of this chronic liver inflammation caused by viruses, their emergence and the importance of early detection.
