The composite eye of the bees, which can be seen in any direction and in an angle of more than 300 degrees, plays an important role.
In order to monitor the function of the composite eye, the researchers took the idea of the laser-controlled distance meter.
This identifies obstacles before the BR23C in a face field of 180 degrees within 2 meters, calculates its distances and sends signals to the microprocessor to board that immediately initiates the collision prevention process.
The obstacle is recorded in second breaks, and the author’s robot immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of the bees, by turning the tyres around the corresponding angle.
Unlike previous systems, this maneuver takes place purely instinctively.
"If not so, the author's robot couldn't react fast enough to avoid obstacles," Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the author's robot project said.
